Anonymous Wed 09 May 2018 23:12:53 No.15670903 Report
Quoted By:
>>15670694
I have a few art friends, and there are a couple reasons for it. It mostly started on character refs, as you said, but it also just became a trend in general. Most artists will have color palettes for a picture on hand for ease of access while doing a drawing, but either keep it separate from the piece or draw over/erase it when they finish. One day (tm) an artist or two decided to just not erase the palette when done with the picture. Why? Because it showed what they were working with as they were drawing.
Including the color palette for general art isn't new though; pixel artists do it all the time, but even then it makes more sense for them to do it as opposed to any reason a digital artist would bother.
It's basically art flair, if that makes any sense. It doesn't actually serve any purpose.

Well, it's still a little too short for me to vomit my thoughts in a sequential order, so I'll just expand on them now. I'm no writer, so take this with a grain of salt.

I noticed you said in >>15673648 that the greentext is a crutch. While this is definitely not a greentext, it still very much reads like one. I'm going to guess either you want to start of slowly for your first foray into the regular stories, or greentext has become second nature so you tell rather than show what's happening. Everything here is merely given a quick snippet and then moved on. A good example is the character's march into town. I have no idea what this place looks like, nor its people. I know it has a marketplace and a central area for bureaucracy. The events are told, then the character teleports to the next location.

Don't get me wrong, I'm quite fond of everything else, but it feels like extended greentext. I have a feeling for the character and what he's going through emotionally, which is perfect. Though his actions, his movement from place to place are all very disconnected. Have you ever been focused on one thing when you're going somewhere and then suddenly you ask yourself "How did I get here?" It's sort of like that. The character is in this kind of cocoon that separates him from the world, or he's sort of fuzzy on the details because he's not really in the world itself, mentally. He talks to the wyverian, and we're told that the Anon explains the situation. And then what? Was he understanding? Clearly he was aware of it happening before, and let Anon pretty much take indefinite vacation, but was he saddened? Surprised? Angry but begrudgingly respectful? How did Anon respond? Despondently? Happily?

I'm basically rambling and seem retarded at this point, but I hope some of my stupidity helped.
